<subSubSection pageId="23" pageNumber="24" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="23.[151,1436,1472,2036]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,327,1849,1875]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
The males of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Simon" baseAuthorityYear="1898" box="[502,702,1850,1875]" class="Arachnida" family="Pisauridae" genus="Architis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="helveola">
<emphasis box="[502,702,1850,1875]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Architis helveola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
share with those of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Simon" baseAuthorityYear="1898" box="[949,1080,1850,1875]" class="Arachnida" family="Pisauridae" genus="Architis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tenuipes">
<emphasis box="[949,1080,1850,1875]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">A. tenuipes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the VTA which is articulated with the apex of the pedipalpal tibia (
<figureCitation box="[590,723,1890,1916]" captionStart="FIGURES 9" captionStartId="21.[151,269,1926,1950]" captionTargetBox="[259,1335,305,1892]" captionTargetId="figure-69@21.[198,1390,254,1930]" captionTargetPageId="21" captionText="FIGURES 9A–D. Architis tenuipes (Simon). A, male pedipalpus, ventral view; B, male pedipalpus, lateral view; C, female epigynum, ventral view; D, female internal genitalia, dorsal view. Scale bars: A–B, 0.2 mm; C–D, 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5097199" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5097199/files/figure.png" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Figs 9A, B</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[736,822,1890,1916]" captionStart="FIGURES 12" captionStartId="24.[151,269,1646,1670]" captionTargetBox="[166,1414,191,1604]" captionTargetId="figure-125@24.[135,1452,150,1648]" captionTargetPageId="24" captionText="FIGURES 12A–E. Architis helveola (Simon). A, female habitus, dorsal view; B, male pedipalpus, ventral view; C, male pedipalpus, lateral view; D, female epigynum, ventral view; E, female internal genitalia, dorsal view. Scale bars: A, 0.5 mm; B–C, 0.2 mm; D–E, 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5097209" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5097209/files/figure.png" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">12B, C</figureCitation>
), but differ by the small vRTA which is not fused to the VTA (
<figureCitation box="[268,414,1930,1956]" captionStart="FIGURES 12" captionStartId="24.[151,269,1646,1670]" captionTargetBox="[166,1414,191,1604]" captionTargetId="figure-125@24.[135,1452,150,1648]" captionTargetPageId="24" captionText="FIGURES 12A–E. Architis helveola (Simon). A, female habitus, dorsal view; B, male pedipalpus, ventral view; C, male pedipalpus, lateral view; D, female epigynum, ventral view; E, female internal genitalia, dorsal view. Scale bars: A, 0.5 mm; B–C, 0.2 mm; D–E, 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5097209" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5097209/files/figure.png" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Figs 12B, C</figureCitation>
). Females can be distinguished from all other 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Simon" authorityYear="1898" box="[956,1048,1930,1955]" class="Arachnida" family="Pisauridae" genus="Architis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[956,1048,1930,1955]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Architis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the medially projected lateral lobes of the epigynum which cover the anterior half of the median field like a pair of keels (
<figureCitation box="[1228,1334,1970,1996]" captionStart="FIGURES 12" captionStartId="24.[151,269,1646,1670]" captionTargetBox="[166,1414,191,1604]" captionTargetId="figure-125@24.[135,1452,150,1648]" captionTargetPageId="24" captionText="FIGURES 12A–E. Architis helveola (Simon). A, female habitus, dorsal view; B, male pedipalpus, ventral view; C, male pedipalpus, lateral view; D, female epigynum, ventral view; E, female internal genitalia, dorsal view. Scale bars: A, 0.5 mm; B–C, 0.2 mm; D–E, 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5097209" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5097209/files/figure.png" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Fig. 12D</figureCitation>
) and the non-encapsulated CD which are shorter than the spermathecae (
<figureCitation box="[898,1004,2010,2036]" captionStart="FIGURES 12" captionStartId="24.[151,269,1646,1670]" captionTargetBox="[166,1414,191,1604]" captionTargetId="figure-125@24.[135,1452,150,1648]" captionTargetPageId="24" captionText="FIGURES 12A–E. Architis helveola (Simon). A, female habitus, dorsal view; B, male pedipalpus, ventral view; C, male pedipalpus, lateral view; D, female epigynum, ventral view; E, female internal genitalia, dorsal view. Scale bars: A, 0.5 mm; B–C, 0.2 mm; D–E, 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5097209" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5097209/files/figure.png" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Fig. 12E</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
